title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer 556, 10" barrel, NOT NFA! LEGAL SHORT BARREL!
postcontent:
I'm thinking about selling this to fund a new project. 
We all love SBR's, but it's such an expensive pain in the rear to get one. But, they're just so damn cool, and unbelievably effective in close quarters scenarios. You could settle for a "pistol", but they're useless, and it just just looks neutered without a stock. This is the alternative, a Sig Sauer 556 with a 10" barrel, and is equipped with the "Sig Brace" butt stock. EOTech is not included. This is NOT an NFA item, and transfers as a pistol, complete with an ATF letter attesting to it's legality. She accepts standard AR mags, and the chrome lined barrel has a proper twist of 1:7, with a long stroke, four way adjustable, piston gas system. The entire bolt assembly is nickel boron coated (NibX), negating the need for lubrication (I still always kept her lubed though). The long stroke piston offers a lower recoil impulse, as the piston is pushing the bolt back....instead of hitting it like a short stroke does. Basically it's a bastard crossbreed between an AR and an AK.  Why settle for one or the other, when you can have their bastard child? You will find the AR 15 style controls and accuracy to be very familiar, and the AK reliability to be very comforting.  I have shot this thing out to 300 meters, and consistently hit my target. With 62gr ammo, she groups about 1 1/2" at 100. I changed the grip to a Hogue overmolded, and included is the stock grip, one steel magazine, and a steel Krinkov (AK 47) style muzzle brake. The original grip is designed for tiny European hands (it causes the top of your hand to dig into the selector). When detaching the flash hider to use a suppressor, I caused a scratch (easily and cheaply replaced) on the crush washer. She also has some normal scuffing behind the ejection port. This is simply caused by the ejected shells, and it does not run to bare metal. I've run around 100+ rounds, and she will eat anything. I have NEVER had ANY failures for this gun...EVER. $1,400, or best reasonable offer. I live in Rowlett, and will drive a little, but I'm not looking for a road trip.

Link to view the legality of the butt stock.
http://www.sigsauer.com/SigStore/sb15-pistol-stabilizing-brace-552.aspx

title: For Sale:  1934 Tula all original Finnish Mosin Nagant 91/30 ****LOOK!!!!****
postcontent:
This one is quite the odd ball. This is a 1934 Tula that was all original when captured by the Finnish during the Winter War or Continuation War. What is interesting about this rifle is the tang date is '34 and the barrel date is 1934, which means the receiver and barrel are original to eachother. Something not common at all about the Finnish Mosin Nagants. The other interesting thing is ALL of the small parts about this rifle are Tula parts and the finish wear matches the rest of the rifle, so unlike most rifles the Finnish captured, they decided this one should stay as it is! It is not counter bored and the bore is mirror sharp! The other interesting thing is that the numbers all match on the rifle (RARE for a Finnish, almost unheard of) however the bolt does not match the rifle. BUT the bolt is all matching to itself and is imperial Izhevsk and the numbers are within 2,000 of the rifle's numbers. So I believe there was something wrong with the original rifle and the Finnish replaced it with a self matching bolt of the time. The stock on this rifle is absolutely stunning and is the best looking stock I have in my collection. The only reason I'm selling it is because I am getting into Mausers. 

I will ship this rifle if you have a C&R license or a FFL. I have 100% positive feedback on multiple sites including Gunbroker and Ebay so feel free to message me and I can prove that. You can email me through here or you can text message me for a faster response. 864-216-370two I can send more pictures if needed.


Good luck, this one shouldn't last long!

title: For Sale:  Walther P38 9mm
postcontent:
Up for sale is a Walther P-38 in great condition.  I've put about 120 flawless rounds through it.  I just don't get out to shoot much and haven't shot since this summer.
The Walther P-38 was designed by Carl Walther and first manufactured by Germany during WWII.  It was only supplanted for the Austrian armed forces by the venerable Glock 17, Gaston Glock's 17th design, and first forray into firearms.  The Walther P-38 has much in common with the Beretta 92.  There's comparison videos and articles that show this.  This is a great shooting gun, is aesthetically unique and iconic, and a nice piece of history.  This is a "post-war" model, made in 1968 in West Germany (based on stamps on the frame).  I hope you enjoy the firearm safely and responsibly.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Stainless HK USP 45 V1 SA/DA w/Original Box & Manual
postcontent:
I'll probably regret selling this HK, but for sale is a very lightly used HK USP 45 Variant 1 with a stainless steel slide (probably the best looking USP ever made), right hand slide release, right hand safety/decocker, night sights (I put a short charge on them and they glowed in the dark), extended magazine release (I'll include the original release if you happen to be one of the 10 people on Earth who doesn't prefer the extended release) and a 12 round magazine.  That's 12+1 of 45 ACP stopping power in the "little brother" of the famous HK Mark 23/SOCOM.  This pistol is amazingly accurate (very nearly as accurate as my HK Expert 40), is exceptionally clean with almost no slide wear and has very little wear on the frame.  It comes with the original case and manual ( and it is the case with the "In a world of compromise, some don't" logo molded in, which pretty much sums up why you run HK pistols.)  

I've put less than 100 rounds through it and I can't imagine based on the internal slide wear it has had more than 500-1000 rounds through it total.  The floor plate on the mag is etched with part of the serial number, but you can get a new floor plate if you want.  It is a Variant 1, so you have a saftey/decocker and can carry this cocked an locked, if you want.  I run the LEM (DAO, really not a double-action, but no safety, no decocker) on the HK's I carry, but I wouldn't hesitate to carry a V1.  

The trigger reset is really good on this and the single action trigger pull is short, smooth and light.  (When I say really good, I mean that a professional operator could run this without an issue, might not be as short as they like, but it is great for 99.99% of shooter.)  The double action pull is good for DA, but you could drop in a match hammer spring and switch to the light trigger block spring if really wanted to get it down a bit more.   I'm not sure if you would want to put the light trigger return spring in this, I think it would be too light, but you could always try it.  I don't generally like DA pulls, so if I think it is good for DA, you will probably be fine.  (Yes, I am really discriminating about triggers and almost every pistol and rifle I own has had its trigger replace/adjusted/modified/smoothed.)

If you don't fully understand the last paragraph, I'll summarize it for you:  It has a really nice trigger.

So why am I selling it?  First, this is the only centerfire pistol I have that isn't 40S&W or .380 ACP and I reload lots of those two calibers, having to reload another caliber and stock it is just kind of a pain for me.  Second, it's a bit big for me to carry concealed, but I think there are a lot of guys who could conceal it just fine.  I'm also selling this to fund a short reset modification to one of my HK carry guns and the purchase of a single stack compact in 40S&W.  

Is $700 expensive?  
Compared to a Glock, yes.  Not for an HK USP 45 with a stainless slide in this condition.  If you are ok with compromises, buy a Glock, they are cheap and ok.

Ohio drivers license required, CCW preferred ( it's nice to know you have at least some level of trianing and hopefully won't have an AD from stupidity.)

Will I ship it?  
Maybe. If you demonstrate on the first email that you have your ducks in a row for shipping, know your state laws and you have an FFL that knows you by name ( by first name is even better.)  If you don't have an FFL that knows you by name, don't bother emailing me, I am not going to ship it to you.  ( Yes, my FFL knows me by first name.  Hell, you could just call him and tell him you need to ship an HK to him for a customer and his first call afetrwards would be to ask me what I was buying.)
